  "key_findings": [
    "SCALE DOMINANCE: The strongest valuation driver is absolute scale — measured by AUM, FEAUM, management fee revenue, FRE, or DE. All are highly multicollinear (rho > 0.91) and capture a single underlying 'scale' factor. Larger firms command systematically higher valuation multiples across all three measures.",
    "MARGIN IRRELEVANCE: FRE margin (rho near zero) has NO cross-sectional relationship with valuation multiples, contradicting the common thesis that margin expansion drives re-rating. Markets price absolute earnings, not margin percentage.",
    "GROWTH RATE IRRELEVANCE: Neither FEAUM growth, FRE growth, nor management fee growth predicts valuation multiples in cross-section. This suggests multiples reflect structural position (scale, franchise) rather than recent momentum.",
    "PERMANENT CAPITAL MYTH: Permanent capital percentage shows no significant relationship with any valuation multiple. The supposed 'permanent capital premium' is not visible in cross-sectional data — possibly because it is already captured by the scale factor.",
    "CREDIT EXPOSURE SIGNAL: Credit strategy percentage shows a moderate positive association with P/FRE (rho=0.52), suggesting markets may be assigning a premium to credit-heavy platforms for their durable, recurring fee characteristics.",
    "ORGANIC GROWTH PROMISE: Net organic growth shows large point estimates (rho=0.60-0.66) but is not yet statistically significant (N=6). If more firms disclosed clean organic growth data, this could emerge as an independent driver."
  ]
